<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many linear feet does a tube of caulk cover?", answer: "A standard 10.1 fl oz caulk tube holds about 18.2 cubic inches of sealant. At a typical 1/4 in × 1/4 in joint (0.0625 sq in cross-section), one tube covers roughly 24 linear feet. Bigger joints use up tubes faster: a 1/2 in × 1/2 in joint uses one tube per 6 linear feet. 20 and 28 fl oz sausage packs cover about 2× and 2.8× as much." },
  { question: "How do I calculate how much caulk I need?", answer: "Multiply the joint length (in inches) by the width and depth to get the joint volume in cubic inches. Divide by the tube volume (18.2 cu in for a standard 10.1 oz tube) and round up, then add 10-20% for waste and bead shape variation. For 30 ft of 1/4 in × 1/4 in joint: 360 × 0.25 × 0.25 = 22.5 cu in ÷ 18.2 ≈ 1.2 tubes → buy 2." },
  { question: "What is the correct bead size for caulking?", answer: "Window and door trim: 1/8 in to 3/16 in bead. Bathtub and tile joints: 1/4 in. Expansion joints in concrete or siding: 1/2 in wide × 1/4 in deep over a backer rod. Cornice and wide gaps: up to 3/4 in. The rule of thumb for good performance is joint depth = half of joint width (with backer rod), so the caulk can stretch and compress without tearing loose." },
  { question: "Should I use a backer rod?", answer: "Yes, for joints wider than 1/4 in. A closed-cell foam backer rod prevents three-sided adhesion (which makes caulk tear), sets the correct depth-to-width ratio (1:2), and saves sealant. Push the rod into the joint with a blunt tool until it sits about half the joint width below the surface, then caulk over it." },
  { question: "How long does caulk last?", answer: "Silicone: 20+ years outdoors. Polyurethane: 10-15 years. Latex acrylic: 5-10 years. The lifespan depends on movement, UV exposure, and joint prep. Caulk fails in three modes — adhesion (peeling off), cohesion (tearing in the middle), or hardening (losing flexibility). Clean, dry joints and proper depth-to-width ratio maximize lifespan." }
]) %>

