    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Calculate Caulk Tubes</h2>
      <p>
        The calculation is straightforward: compute the total volume of sealant you need to fill, then divide by the volume of your chosen tube. <strong>Joint volume = length × width × depth</strong>, all in the same units. A standard 10.1 fl oz caulk cartridge holds about 18.2 cubic inches of sealant. Divide your joint volume by 18.2, round up, and add 10-20% for bead shape variation and waste from tooling the bead. Always buy one extra tube beyond the calculation — tubes dry out partway through, drop and split, or run out on the last 3 ft of baseboard.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Joint Sizing and Depth-to-Width Ratio</h2>
      <p>
        A well-sized joint has a depth-to-width ratio of about 1:2 — a 1/2 inch wide joint should be 1/4 inch deep. This ratio lets the caulk flex without tearing. Narrow joints (under 1/4 in) can be depth-equal or slightly shallower. Very wide joints (over 1/2 in) require a closed-cell foam backer rod behind the caulk to set the right depth and prevent three-sided adhesion. A backer rod is not optional on exterior expansion joints — without it the caulk will crack within a few freeze-thaw cycles.
      </p>

      <h3>Common Caulking Jobs</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Window and door trim:</strong> 1/8 inch bead, one tube covers about 96 ft. <strong>Bathtub and tile:</strong> 1/4 inch × 1/4 inch, one tube covers 24 ft. <strong>Exterior siding expansion joints:</strong> 3/8 inch × 1/4 inch with backer rod, one tube covers 16 ft. <strong>Concrete control joints:</strong> 1/2 inch × 1/4 inch with backer rod, one tube covers 12 ft. <strong>Crown molding and baseboard:</strong> 1/8 inch paintable acrylic, one tube covers about 100 linear feet.
      </p>

      <h3>Tube Types</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>10.1 fl oz cartridges</strong> (standard caulk gun size) are the most common. <strong>20 fl oz sausage packs</strong> are popular with pros because they change out faster and waste less packaging. <strong>28 fl oz packs</strong> are used for large expansion joints and cost less per ounce. Buy sausage packs if you will use more than 4 tubes worth — they save time and money.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How many linear feet per 10 oz tube?</h3>
      <p>At 1/4 × 1/4 joint: 24 ft. At 1/8 × 1/8: 96 ft. At 1/2 × 1/4: 12 ft. Depends entirely on bead size.</p>

      <h3>What waste factor should I use?</h3>
      <p>10% for straight runs with few stops. 20-25% for lots of corners, detail work, or when applying caulk outdoors in cold weather (tubes set faster).</p>

      <h3>Do different caulks yield differently?</h3>
      <p>Tube volume is the same for a given package size regardless of chemistry. Silicone, latex, polyurethane — 10.1 oz cartridge holds 10.1 oz of sealant in all of them.</p>

      <h3>Is a tube the same as a cartridge?</h3>
      <p>Yes — caulk "tube" and "cartridge" are interchangeable for the standard 10.1 fl oz size. "Sausage pack" specifically means the flexible foil bag (20 or 28 oz) that needs a bulk gun.</p>

      <h3>Should I buy more than calculated?</h3>
      <p>Yes — always buy at least one extra tube. Opened tubes don't store well and you will always need a little more than you think.</p>

